And I always wonder when are you going to

01:00:53.990 --> 01:01:01.960
plan to travel to Russia?
Saint Petersburg, Golden Gate, Ring around

01:01:01.960 --> 01:01:02.960
the Moscow would be
fantastic sites for you to explore with the

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:03.960
rest of us?

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:04.960
RICK STEVES: The question is when am I going
to go to Russia.

01:01:04.960 --> 01:01:08.540
As soon as Russia learns how to welcome tourists
with no visa and

01:01:08.540 --> 01:01:12.320
better, well-organized, fair system for hotels.
I love going to Russia.

01:01:12.320 --> 01:01:15.990
It's beautiful to go there.
Saint Petersburg is one of my favorite cities,

01:01:15.990 --> 01:01:19.160
really.
And we take our tours there with Helsinki

01:01:19.160 --> 01:01:24.310
and Estonia.
But it's -- Russia's going to warm up to that.

01:01:24.310 --> 01:01:25.870
And I think it's great for people to go to
Russia.

01:01:25.870 --> 01:01:30.250
But from a mass tourism point of view, it's
still -- I am not convinced

01:01:30.250 --> 01:01:35.420
that the infrastructure is there with a -- sort
of a price for locals

01:01:35.420 --> 01:01:38.730
that's not gouging them.
And the visa thing is frustrating to me.

01:01:38.730 --> 01:01:40.830
But obviously it's going happen and it's very
exciting.

01:01:40.830 --> 01:01:44.110
As soon as Russia's opened up to tourism more,
I'm going to make a TV

01:01:44.110 --> 01:01:46.020
show there for sure.
Next?

01:01:46.020 --> 01:01:47.250
&gt;&gt;Thanks for coming.

01:01:47.250 --> 01:01:48.490
RICK STEVES: Yeah.

01:01:48.490 --> 01:01:52.150
&gt;&gt;You mentioned Europe as a new modern place,
and Berlin obviously is

01:01:52.150 --> 01:01:55.310
very modern.
So I like to see things like architecture

01:01:55.310 --> 01:01:59.490
and new cities and things
like that so -- are there any highlights that

01:01:59.490 --> 01:02:00.490
you would mention?

01:02:00.490 --> 01:02:03.500
RICK STEVES: Well, I love skyscrapers and
modern cities, like I showed

01:02:03.500 --> 01:02:08.090
three slides there.
And I've found that in many cities, they protect

01:02:08.090 --> 01:02:11.610
the skyline in the
downtown core because they don't want modern

01:02:11.610 --> 01:02:14.910
architecture obliterating
beautiful domes and historic spires.

01:02:14.910 --> 01:02:19.000
Outside of that protected area, that's where
you get the Manhattan.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:21.500
And I think it's really important when you're
a tourist to find out

01:02:21.500 --> 01:02:24.610
where are the people working, where's the
real work-a-day life.

01:02:24.610 --> 01:02:27.200
And take the commuter train out there and
wander through just the

01:02:27.200 --> 01:02:31.240
modern skyscraper Manhattan kind of areas.
Because there's lot of modern art there, there's

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:32.240
beautiful skyscraper
architecture.

01:02:32.240 --> 01:02:35.890
And there's a vibrancy you don't feel in the
touristic old core.

01:02:35.890 --> 01:02:38.180
Yeah.
But man, there's great modern architecture

01:02:38.180 --> 01:02:40.090
all over Europe these days.

01:02:40.090 --> 01:02:41.090
&gt;&gt;Thank you.

01:02:41.090 --> 01:02:42.090
RICK STEVES: Yeah.

01:02:42.090 --> 01:02:48.090
&gt;&gt;Hi, thanks for coming.
I found lots of really nice places in Europe

01:02:48.090 --> 01:02:49.580
and I live in constant
terror that you will one day put them in one

01:02:49.580 --> 01:02:51.630
of your books, and they'll
be ruined for me.

01:02:51.630 --> 01:02:52.630
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:52.630 --> 01:02:57.260
RICK STEVES: If I give you my e-mail address
maybe you can send me a

01:02:57.260 --> 01:02:59.400
list and I'll -- I promise I won't put them
in anything.

01:02:59.400 --> 01:03:01.360
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:01.360 --> 01:03:08.330
&gt;&gt; So, I mean, seriously.
You know, I myself worry when I write up a

01:03:08.330 --> 01:03:10.415
place on my blog.
You know, how do you reconcile, well, you

01:03:10.415 --> 01:03:11.670
know, this is a cool place.
I'd like to tell people about it but you know

01:03:11.670 --> 01:03:17.500
it definitely cannot
tolerate 200 visitors a day.

01:03:17.500 --> 01:03:20.970
RICK STEVES: Well, that's a very good question
and it's an issue that

01:03:20.970 --> 01:03:23.640
I do think about.
I go back to my favorite places -- I don't

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:26.710
know if you know the Cinque
Terre, for instance is a little villages,

01:03:26.710 --> 01:03:28.050
five villages in the Italian
Rivera.

01:03:28.050 --> 01:03:30.721
And every time I go there, I'm a little nervous
because it gets more

01:03:30.721 --> 01:03:34.740
and more touristy, you know.
And all of a sudden, nobody is -- nobody is

01:03:34.740 --> 01:03:38.180
picking the grapes anymore.
All the grape fields are just going to waste.

01:03:38.180 --> 01:03:40.690
And everybody's got their cyber cafes and
their laundromats and their

01:03:40.690 --> 01:03:44.090
little boutique hotels and so on.
And I come into town every year or two and

01:03:44.090 --> 01:03:47.110
local people are thrilled to
see me because I'm stoking their economy,

01:03:47.110 --> 01:03:49.190
the tourists are just having
a blast.

01:03:49.190 --> 01:03:52.250
And then there's always a few people like
you that think I should have

01:03:52.250 --> 01:03:57.390
kept it a secret.
And I'm not -- my job is not to protect these

01:03:57.390 --> 01:04:00.400
places.
I'm sort of like the hired hand to find them.

01:04:00.400 --> 01:04:02.840
And what I would say, there are places that
I find that really could

01:04:02.840 --> 01:04:05.790
not handle the crowds.
And I would never promote a place that really

01:04:05.790 --> 01:04:08.470
didn't welcome the crowds
or couldn't handle the crowds.

01:04:08.470 --> 01:04:11.250
And what I need to do is to try and find more
places so I can spread

01:04:11.250 --> 01:04:13.810
the crowds out a little bit.
But it's an interesting issue.

01:04:13.810 --> 01:04:17.070
And it's a nice problem for a travel writer
to have to have that much

01:04:17.070 --> 01:04:19.190
of an impact on a place.
I wish I could find more Cinque Terres, and

01:04:19.190 --> 01:04:21.080
I wish I could find more
Gimmelwalds.

01:04:21.080 --> 01:04:26.090
There are more Cinque Terres but they're not
as accessible as the Cinque Terre that I've

01:04:26.090 --> 01:04:29.480
been pushing because it's just two hours away
from Florence or the Leaning Tower of Pisa

01:04:29.480 --> 01:04:32.610
where everybody goes anyways.
If you go down to the Pardi Islands or down

01:04:32.610 --> 01:04:35.930
around Sicily, there's a
lot of places just about as magical.

01:04:35.930 --> 01:04:42.120
But they're different.
So I'm just -- yeah, it's just I'm just doing

01:04:42.120 --> 01:04:43.120
my best it ruin these
places.

01:04:43.120 --> 01:04:44.980
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:51.880
&gt;&gt;Last year I was in Switzerland's Chalet
Fontana, one of the places

01:04:51.880 --> 01:04:53.860
mentioned in the book.
It was completely swamped of English speakers.

01:04:53.860 --> 01:04:56.860
A couple of months later, I went to the other
side of the Ebenese

01:04:56.860 --> 01:04:58.660
Overland, everybody was German, everybody
 --

01:04:58.660 --> 01:05:03.860
RICK STEVES: Yeah, yeah. That's for sure.
Did you meet Denise there at Chalet Fontana?

01:05:03.860 --> 01:05:04.860
&gt;&gt;Yes, I did.

01:05:04.860 --> 01:05:07.000
RICK STEVES: Yeah, she's the wonderful lady
that runs that.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:11.320
You know, Americans go to the same places.
And the Germans go to the same places.

01:05:11.320 --> 01:05:15.050
And people with my book go to the same places.
It's just a reality.

01:05:15.050 --> 01:05:21.860
And I -- I remind people if you want to not
see Americans, you're

01:05:21.860 --> 01:05:25.850
holding the wrong book.
You know, I'm trying to spread it out.

01:05:25.850 --> 01:05:28.890
Now having said that, we've been talking about
the marque destinations.

01:05:28.890 --> 01:05:32.770
Honestly, I just spent ten days in Basque
Country, in Galicia

01:05:32.770 --> 01:05:37.580
Northwestern Spain.
And I write about it enthusiastically and

01:05:37.580 --> 01:05:40.990
in 10 days, I probably saw
ten people with my book.

01:05:40.990 --> 01:05:46.690
I just spent 20 days across Scandinavia.
And in 20 days, maybe a saw a hundred people

01:05:46.690 --> 01:05:50.620
with my book.
And then I go to Rome and in one day, I see

01:05:50.620 --> 01:05:54.750
300 people with my book.
So it's really interesting, we all are inclined

01:05:54.750 --> 01:05:57.250
to go to the same
marque destinations.

01:05:57.250 --> 01:06:00.200
But if you want to go to Estonia, you're going
to find a back door

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:02.640
wonderland.
And you've got all the information -- if you

01:06:02.640 --> 01:06:04.850
like my information,
you'll have it because I cover it.

01:06:04.850 --> 01:06:09.310
But Americans don't go there.
If I just wrote books on places that sold

01:06:09.310 --> 01:06:12.900
well, I would drop my
Scandinavia book and I wouldn't be covering

01:06:12.900 --> 01:06:16.460
Galicia.
So I have to be realistic.

01:06:16.460 --> 01:06:20.200
I'm a business and I'm not going to write
a book to Moldavia because it

01:06:20.200 --> 01:06:23.780
would be very expensive to do and it would
change really fast.

01:06:23.780 --> 01:06:26.980
And nobody would -- in relative terms, nobody
would go there.

01:06:26.980 --> 01:06:30.160
I wrote a book once to the former Soviet Union
and it sold in the

01:06:30.160 --> 01:06:32.120
hundreds.
You know, you've got to be tuned in.

01:06:32.120 --> 01:06:35.880
I'd write a book to Paris and it subsidizes
all those other books.

01:06:35.880 --> 01:06:39.430
So that's just an interesting little business
thing I have to consider.

01:06:39.430 --> 01:06:40.430
Yeah?

01:06:40.430 --> 01:06:41.870
&gt;&gt;With the growing popularity of the automated
machines for tickets and

01:06:41.870 --> 01:06:43.810
so on -- but a lot of them only take chip
and PIN cards.

01:06:43.810 --> 01:06:50.610
Is there any movement on being able, for Americans
to be able to get

01:06:50.610 --> 01:06:51.870
one of those?

01:06:51.870 --> 01:06:55.080
RICK STEVES: You know, that's a good issue.
And I'm not -- I'm not very -- I don't have

01:06:55.080 --> 01:06:56.850
much of an appetite to
learn about that.

01:06:56.850 --> 01:07:02.890
I've got a graffiti wall on my website.
It's our version of -- Lonely Planet has the

01:07:02.890 --> 01:07:04.130
Thorn Bush or something
like that.

01:07:04.130 --> 01:07:07.790
And I -- I ask the perplexing questions like
that and I let everybody

01:07:07.790 --> 01:07:11.480
who has got experience share their information.
If you went to the ricksteves.com graffiti

01:07:11.480 --> 01:07:16.600
wall, and look in there
under technical challenges or credit card

01:07:16.600 --> 01:07:18.960
issues or whatever, you'd
find a lot of people talking about that.

01:07:18.960 --> 01:07:21.760
But that is a frustration for a lot of Americans
is that Europeans have

01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:24.850
a little chip embedded in their card that
makes our card not work.

01:07:24.850 --> 01:07:29.790
You can always use our card to get cash.
And I almost exclusively get my -- I use my

01:07:29.790 --> 01:07:32.780
ATM to get hard cash and I
spent hard cash.

01:07:32.780 --> 01:07:35.820
I find that's the best deal.
But there are -- there is a frustration about

01:07:35.820 --> 01:07:37.380
that.
And I hope that that gets straightened out.

01:07:37.380 --> 01:07:42.460
I'm sure there's people working on that but
I don't choose it get into

01:07:42.460 --> 01:07:43.460
it.

01:07:43.460 --> 01:07:47.050
&gt;&gt;So, I've personally experienced problems
with trying to plan with

01:07:47.050 --> 01:07:56.120
others in there's a lot of people who either
experience a lot of

01:07:56.120 --> 01:08:00.780
anxiety about, say, going off the beaten path
or not do tour groups or

01:08:00.780 --> 01:08:01.780
even doing something like staying at two-star
hotel.

01:08:01.780 --> 01:08:02.780
They are very much focused on the main touristy
areas.

01:08:02.780 --> 01:08:07.910
Do you have any suggestions for people who
want to travel with others

01:08:07.910 --> 01:08:11.340
on convincing the people they want to travel
with to sort of take this

01:08:11.340 --> 01:08:14.050
more holistic view, and really spend, you
know, instead of visiting

01:08:14.050 --> 01:08:18.510
four countries in two weeks, spending some
time really getting to know

01:08:18.510 --> 01:08:19.510
a place.

01:08:19.510 --> 01:08:21.290
RICK STEVES: So you've got friends who are
front door travellers and

01:08:21.290 --> 01:08:23.100
you're a back door traveler?

01:08:23.100 --> 01:08:26.870
&gt;&gt;Well they're first-time travellers. They
have a lot of anxiety about

01:08:26.870 --> 01:08:28.300
being a back door traveller.

01:08:28.300 --> 01:08:30.480
RICK STEVES: Anxiety because they're going
to be physically roughing

01:08:30.480 --> 01:08:33.640
it or because they're going to places that
aren't featured in Conde

01:08:33.640 --> 01:08:34.640
Nast?

01:08:34.640 --> 01:08:41.900
&gt;&gt;Anxiety because they have no past expectations.
For example, they don't realize how easy it

01:08:41.900 --> 01:08:46.460
is to find an English
speaker in Western Europe.

01:08:46.460 --> 01:08:47.460
Or the fact that you can --

01:08:47.460 --> 01:08:49.290
RICK STEVES: Well, it sounds like they need
to be drugged and dragged

01:08:49.290 --> 01:08:54.440
over there and then introduced to it.
So that they realize that their fears --

01:08:54.440 --> 01:08:56.230
&gt;&gt;Stage one complete, but --
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:56.230 --> 01:08:57.230
-- more ideas.

01:08:57.230 --> 01:09:00.390
RICK STEVES: Once they did one trip, they'd
be fine.

01:09:00.390 --> 01:09:07.650
If you went to -- you if -- I don't know.
If you go it my website and look at some of

01:09:07.650 --> 01:09:10.750
the chatter of people who
have travelled there, if you go it my tour

01:09:10.750 --> 01:09:14.770
section and see the online
scrapbooks that people have made, you can

01:09:14.770 --> 01:09:18.170
see how there's real normal
travellers that are inclined to take normal

01:09:18.170 --> 01:09:21.870
tours that have been --
found their way into this and really have

01:09:21.870 --> 01:09:24.970
their apprehensions overcome
by their own experience.

01:09:24.970 --> 01:09:29.390
But some people you can't force to be back
door travellers.

01:09:29.390 --> 01:09:34.120
And that's probably good news for the rest
of us who are back door

01:09:34.120 --> 01:09:35.120
travellers.

01:09:35.120 --> 01:09:36.120
&gt;&gt;Thank you.

01:09:36.120 --> 01:09:39.150
RICK STEVES: So don't work too hard on it,
please.

01:09:39.150 --> 01:09:43.230
&gt;&gt;All right.
So I don't actually have a question for you,

01:09:43.230 --> 01:09:47.060
Rick.
But I just wanted to tell everyone here that

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:48.380
you're going to stick
around for a few minutes to do autographs.

01:09:48.380 --> 01:09:50.370
So for people who are interested in that,
please start lining up at the

01:09:50.370 --> 01:09:51.370
front.
Oh my God, that's everyone.

01:09:51.370 --> 01:09:52.370
RICK STEVES: All right.

01:09:52.370 --> 01:09:53.370
&gt;&gt;All right. Thanks.

01:09:53.370 --> 01:09:54.370
RICK STEVES: All right, good. thank you very
much.

01:09:54.370 --> 01:09:55.370
It's fun to be here.

